<author><name><![CDATA[Super-Hampster]]></name></author>
<updated>2011-07-13T00:54:12-07:00</updated>
<published>2011-07-13T00:54:12-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7960&amp;p=81489#p81489</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7960&amp;p=81489#p81489"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[NES sound mod]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=7960&amp;p=81489#p81489"><![CDATA[
Sure. You need a 100k ohm resistor and a 4.7uF Capacitor. Use them to connect the audio out pin of your Famicom cart to pin 3 on the expansion port. <br /><br />famicom cart pin 46 --&gt; 100k ohm resistor --&gt; 4.7uF Capacitor --&gt; pin 3 of NES expansion port. <br /><br />I used test probe wire and the copper wire out of a cat5 cable. Here are some pics. <br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/adaptermod3.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/adaptermod2.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/adaptermod.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/audiomod1.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/capandresistor.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/audiomod2.jpg" alt="Image" /><br /><br /><img src="http://img.photobucket.com/albums/v107/super-hampster/NES%20audio%20mod/nesblack.jpg" alt="Image" /><p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=493">Super-Hampster</a> — Wed Jul 13, 2011 12:54 am</p><hr />
